◆ CalibrationType

enum class CalibrationType
strong

Supported calibration types.

Enumerator
Bootstrap 

Choose this option if the component's calibration strategy is expected to yield a perfect match of model to market prices. For example, this can be achieved when calibrating an IR component to a series of co-terminal swaptions with given mean reversion speed and piecewise volatility function (alpha) where jump times coincide with expiry dates in the swaption basket. Similarly, when calibrating an FX component to a series of FX Options. The calibration routine will throw an exception if no perfect match is achieved.

BestFit 

Choose this if no perfect match like above can be expected, for example when an IR component with constant parameters is calibrated to a basket of swaptions. The calibration routine will consequently not throw an exception when the match is imperfect.

None 

No calibration

◆ buildPseudoCurrencyMarketParameters()

struct PseudoCurrencyMarketParameters buildPseudoCurrencyMarketParameters ( const std::map< string, string > &  pricingEngineGlobalParameters = std::map< string, string >())

Function to build parameters from PricingEngine GlobalParametrs.

If no PricingEngine Global Parameters (PEGP) are provided the default params are returned which have treatAsFX = true. If PEGP are present, we look for the following fields

name="PseudoCurrency.TreatAsFX" value = true or false name="PseudoCurrency.BaseCurrency" value = currency code name="PseudoCurrency.FXIndexTag" value = Tag name for FX indices, e.g. GENERIC means we request correlation for "FX-GENERIC-USD-EUR" name="PseudeoCurrency.Curves.XXX" value = curve name, here XXX should be a 3 letter Precious metal or Crypto currency code name="PseudoCurrency.DefaultCorrelation" value = correlation. This is optional, if present we use this when the market has no correlation

A typical configuration is <pre> <GlobalParameters> <Parameter name="PseudoCurrency.TreatAsFX">false</Parameter> <Parameter name="PseudoCurrency.BaseCurrency">USD</Parameter> <Parameter name="PseudoCurrency.FXIndexTag">GENERIC</Parameter> <Parameter name="PseudoCurrency.Curve.XAU">PM:XAUUSD</Parameter> <Parameter name="PseudoCurrency.Curve.XBT">CRYPTO:XBTUSD</Parameter> </GlobalParameters> </pre>

Definition at line 53 of file market.cpp.

53 {
54 PseudoCurrencyMarketParameters params;
55
56 // default
57 params.treatAsFX = true;
58
59 auto it = pegp.find("PseudoCurrency.TreatAsFX");
60 if (it != pegp.end()) {
61 DLOG("Building PseudoCurrencyMarketParameters from PricingEngine GlobalParameters");
62 try {
63 // Build the params
64 params.treatAsFX = parseBool(it->second);
65 it = pegp.find("PseudoCurrency.BaseCurrency");
66 QL_REQUIRE(it != pegp.end(), "No BaseCurrency field");
67 params.baseCurrency = it->second;
68 parseCurrency(params.baseCurrency); // to check it is valid
69
70 // Now just search for the 4 precious metals and 7 crypto currencies
71 for (const string& pm : CurrencyParser::instance().pseudoCurrencyCodes()) {
72 it = pegp.find("PseudoCurrency.Curve." + pm);
73 if (it != pegp.end())
74 params.curves[pm] = it->second;
75 }
76 QL_REQUIRE(!params.curves.empty(), "At least one PM Curve required");
77
78 // Look for fxIndexTag
79 it = pegp.find("PseudoCurrency.FXIndexTag");
80 QL_REQUIRE(it != pegp.end(), "No FXIndexTag field");
81 params.fxIndexTag = it->second;
82
83 // Look for Optional default correlation
84 it = pegp.find("PseudoCurrency.DefaultCorrelation");
85 if (it == pegp.end()) {
86 LOG("No Default Correlation present");
87 params.defaultCorrelation = Null<Real>();
88 } else {
89 LOG("Default Correlation is \"" << it->second << "\"");
90 params.defaultCorrelation = parseReal(it->second);
91 QL_REQUIRE(-1.0 <= params.defaultCorrelation && params.defaultCorrelation <= 1.0,
92 "Invalid DefaultCorrelation value " << it->second);
93 }
94 } catch (std::exception& e) {
95 QL_FAIL("Failed to build PseudoCurrencyMarketParameters : " << e.what());
96 }
97 } else {
98 DLOG("Building default PseudoCurrencyMarketParameters");
99 }
100 DLOG(params);
101
102 return params;
103}

◆ parseBaseStrike()

boost::shared_ptr< BaseStrike > parseBaseStrike ( const string &  strStrike)

Parse a Strike from its string representation, strStrike.

Definition at line 262 of file strike.cpp.

262 {
263
264 boost::shared_ptr<BaseStrike> strike;
265
266 // Expect strStrike to either:
267 // 1. have a single token which means that we have an absolute strike, or
268 // 2. have multiple tokens beginning with one of DEL, ATM or MNY
269 vector<string> tokens;
270 boost::split(tokens, strStrike, boost::is_any_of("/"));
271
272 if (tokens.size() == 1) {
273 strike = boost::make_shared<AbsoluteStrike>();
274 } else if (tokens[0] == "DEL") {
275 strike = boost::make_shared<DeltaStrike>();
276 } else if (tokens[0] == "ATM") {
277 strike = boost::make_shared<AtmStrike>();
278 } else if (tokens[0] == "MNY") {
279 strike = boost::make_shared<MoneynessStrike>();
280 } else {
281 QL_FAIL("Could not parse strike string '" << strStrike << "'.");
282 }
283
284 strike->fromString(strStrike);
285
286 return strike;
287}

111 yieldts.reset(new CurveType<QuantLib::LogLinear>(dates, rates, dayCounter, QuantLib::LogLinear()));
112 break;
113 case YieldCurve::InterpolationMethod::NaturalCubic:
114 yieldts.reset(new CurveType<QuantLib::Cubic>(dates, rates, dayCounter,
115 QuantLib::Cubic(CubicInterpolation::Kruger, true)));
116 break;
117 case YieldCurve::InterpolationMethod::FinancialCubic:
118 yieldts.reset(new CurveType<QuantLib::Cubic>(dates, rates, dayCounter,
119 QuantLib::Cubic(CubicInterpolation::Kruger, true,
120 CubicInterpolation::SecondDerivative, 0.0,
121 CubicInterpolation::FirstDerivative)));
122 break;
123 case YieldCurve::InterpolationMethod::ConvexMonotone:
124 yieldts.reset(
125 new CurveType<QuantLib::ConvexMonotone>(dates, rates, dayCounter, Calendar(), {}, {}, QuantLib::ConvexMonotone()));
126 break;
127 case YieldCurve::InterpolationMethod::Quadratic:
128 yieldts.reset(new CurveType<QuantExt::Quadratic>(dates, rates, dayCounter, QuantExt::Quadratic(1, 0, 1, 0, 1)));
129 break;
130 case YieldCurve::InterpolationMethod::LogQuadratic:
131 yieldts.reset(
132 new CurveType<QuantExt::LogQuadratic>(dates, rates, dayCounter, QuantExt::LogQuadratic(1, 0, -1, 0, 1)));
133 break;
134 case YieldCurve::InterpolationMethod::Hermite:
135 yieldts.reset(new CurveType<QuantLib::Cubic>(dates, rates, dayCounter, Cubic(CubicInterpolation::Parabolic)));
136 break;
137 case YieldCurve::InterpolationMethod::CubicSpline:
138 yieldts.reset(new CurveType<QuantLib::Cubic>(dates, rates, dayCounter,
139 Cubic(CubicInterpolation::Spline, false,
140 CubicInterpolation::SecondDerivative, 0.0,
141 CubicInterpolation::SecondDerivative, 0.0)));
142 break;
143 default:
144 QL_FAIL("Interpolation method not recognised.");
145 }
146 return yieldts;
147}

305 // report alpha, H at t_expiry^-
306 t = inflationYearFraction(
307 parametrization->termStructure()->frequency(), indexIsInterpolated,
308 parametrization->termStructure()->dayCounter(), parametrization->termStructure()->baseDate(),

311 modelH = parametrization->H(t - 1.0 / 250.0);
312 }

314 log << std::setw(3) << j << std::setprecision(6) << std::setw(14) << t << std::setw(14) << modelValue
315 << std::setw(14) << marketValue << std::setw(14) << valueDiff << std::setw(14) << modelAlpha
316 << std::setw(14) << modelH << "\n";
317 }
318 if (parametrization != nullptr) {
319 // report alpha, kappa at t_expiry^+ for last expiry
320 modelAlpha = parametrization->alpha(t + 1.0 / 250.0);
321 modelH = parametrization->H(t + 1.0 / 2500.0);
322 }
323 log << "t >= " << t << ": infDkAlpha = " << modelAlpha << " infDkH = " << modelH << "\n";
324 return log.str();

std::vector< Handle< DefaultProbabilityTermStructure > > buildPerformanceOptimizedDefaultCurves ( const std::vector< Handle< DefaultProbabilityTermStructure > > &  curves)

Disable sensitivites for the all but the first default probability curve Shift all other curves parallel with the first curve, reduce the numbers of calculations

Definition at line 40 of file cdo.cpp.

40 {
41 std::vector<Handle<DefaultProbabilityTermStructure>> dpts;
42 Handle<DefaultProbabilityTermStructure> clientCurve;
43 Handle<DefaultProbabilityTermStructure> baseCurve;
44 vector<Time> baseCurveTimes;
45
46 for (const auto& targetCurve : curves) {
47 //For all but the first curve use a spreaded curve, with the first curve as reference and
48 //the inital spread between the curve and the first curve, keep the spread constant
49 //in case of a spreaded curve we need to use the underlying reference curve to retrieve the
50 //correct pillar times, otherwise the interpolation grid is to coarse and we wouldnt match
51 //today's market prices
52 vector<Time> targetCurveTimes = ore::data::SyntheticCDO::extractTimeGridDefaultCurve(targetCurve);
53 // Sort times we need to interpolate an all pillars of the base and target curve
54 std::sort(targetCurveTimes.begin(), targetCurveTimes.end());
55 // Use the first curve as basis curve and update times
56 if (targetCurve == curves.front()) {
57 baseCurve = targetCurve;
58 clientCurve = baseCurve;
59 baseCurveTimes = targetCurveTimes;
60 } else {
61 std::vector<Time> times;
62 std::set_union(baseCurveTimes.begin(), baseCurveTimes.end(), targetCurveTimes.begin(),
63 targetCurveTimes.end(), std::back_inserter(times));
64 vector<Handle<Quote>> spreads(times.size());
65 std::transform(times.begin(), times.end(), spreads.begin(), [&baseCurve, &targetCurve](Time t) {
66 Probability spread =
67 targetCurve->survivalProbability(t, true) / baseCurve->survivalProbability(t, true);
68 if (close_enough(spread, 0.0)) {
69 spread = 1e-18;
70 }
71 return Handle<Quote>(boost::make_shared<SimpleQuote>(spread));
72 });
73 clientCurve = Handle<DefaultProbabilityTermStructure>(
74 boost::make_shared<SpreadedSurvivalProbabilityTermStructure>(baseCurve, times, spreads));
75 if (baseCurve->allowsExtrapolation())
76 clientCurve->enableExtrapolation();
77 }
78 dpts.push_back(clientCurve);
79 }
80 return dpts;

◆ amendInflationFixingDates() [2/2]

void amendInflationFixingDates ( std::map< std::string, std::set< QuantLib::Date > > &  fixings)

Inflation fixings are generally available on a monthly, or coarser, frequency. When a portfolio is asked for its fixings, and it contains inflation fixings, ORE will by convention put the fixing date as the 1st day of the applicable inflation period. Some market data providers by convention supply the inflation fixings with the date as the last date of the applicable inflation period. This function scans the fixings map, and moves any inflation fixing dates from the 1st day of the inflation period to the last day of the inflation period. The key in the fixings map is the index name and the value is the set of dates for which we require the fixings.

If inflation indices have been set up via ZeroInflationIndex entries in the Conventions, the conventions should be passed here. If not, the default nullptr parameter will be sufficient.

◆ addMarketFixingDates() [2/2]

void addMarketFixingDates ( const QuantLib::Date &  asof,
std::map< std::string, std::set< QuantLib::Date > > &  fixings,
const TodaysMarketParameters &  mktParams,
const QuantLib::Period &  iborLookback = 5 *QuantLib::Days,
const QuantLib::Period &  oisLookback = 4 *QuantLib::Months,
const QuantLib::Period &  bmaLookback = 2 *QuantLib::Weeks,
const QuantLib::Period &  inflationLookback = 1 *QuantLib::Years 
)

Add index and fixing date pairs to fixings that will be potentially needed to build a TodaysMarket.

These additional index and fixing date pairs are found by scanning the mktParams and:

  • for MarketObject::IndexCurve, take the ibor index name and add the dates for each weekday between settlement date minus iborLookback period or oisLookback period and settlement date. The distinction between Ibor and OIS is made here to cover the fixings necessary for OIS futures. The default value of 4 months covers OIS futures with a contract period of up to 3 months. It would need to be configured differently if OIS futures with a longer contract period are possible.
  • for MarketObject::ZeroInflationCurve, take the inflation index and add the first of each month between settlement date minus inflationLookback period and settlement date
  • for MarketObject::YoYInflationCurve, take the inflation index and add the first of each month between settlement date minus inflationLookback period and settlement date
  • for MarketObject::CommodityCurve, add fixings for future contracts expiring 2 months either side of the settlement date. The fixing dates are added for each weekday going back to the first day of the month that precedes the settlement date by 2 months. The approach here will give rise to some spot commodities being given a future contract name and dates added against them - this should not be a problem as there will be no fixings found for them in any case.

The original fixings map may be empty.

1467 .withFixingDays(floatData->fixingDays())
1468 .withRateCutoff(floatData->rateCutoff() == Null<Size>() ? 0 : floatData->rateCutoff())

1470 Null<Real>()))
1471 .withFloors(buildScheduledVectorNormalised<Real>(floatData->floors(), floatData->capDates(),
1472 schedule, Null<Real>()))
1473 .withNakedOption(floatData->nakedOption())

1475 .withOvernightIndexedCouponPricer(couponPricer)
1476 .withCapFlooredOvernightIndexedCouponPricer(cfCouponPricer)
1477 .withTelescopicValueDates(floatData->telescopicValueDates())
1478 .withPaymentDates(paymentDates);
1479
1480 // If the overnight index is BRL CDI, we need a special coupon pricer
1481 boost::shared_ptr<BRLCdi> brlCdiIndex = boost::dynamic_pointer_cast<BRLCdi>(index);
1482 if (brlCdiIndex)
1483 QuantExt::setCouponPricer(leg, boost::make_shared<BRLCdiCouponPricer>());
1484
1485 return leg;

1564 {
1565
1566 // Assumption - Cashflows on Input Leg are all coupons
1567 // This is the Leg to be populated
1568 Leg leg;
1569
1570 // Initial Flow Amount
1571 if (initNomFlow) {
1572 auto coupon = boost::dynamic_pointer_cast<QuantLib::Coupon>(refLeg[0]);
1573 QL_REQUIRE(coupon, "makeNotionalLeg does not support non-coupon legs");
1574 double initFlowAmt = (excludeIndexing ? unpackIndexedCoupon(coupon) : coupon)->nominal();
1575 Date initDate = coupon->accrualStartDate();
1576 initDate = paymentCalendar.advance(initDate, paymentLag, Days, paymentConvention);
1577 if (initFlowAmt != 0)
1578 leg.push_back(boost::shared_ptr<CashFlow>(new SimpleCashFlow(-initFlowAmt, initDate)));
1579 }
1580
1581 // Amortization Flows
1582 if (amortNomFlow) {
1583 for (Size i = 1; i < refLeg.size(); i++) {
1584 auto coupon = boost::dynamic_pointer_cast<QuantLib::Coupon>(refLeg[i]);
1585 QL_REQUIRE(coupon, "makeNotionalLeg does not support non-coupon legs");
1586 auto coupon2 = boost::dynamic_pointer_cast<QuantLib::Coupon>(refLeg[i - 1]);
1587 QL_REQUIRE(coupon, "makeNotionalLeg does not support non-coupon legs");
1588 Date flowDate = coupon->accrualStartDate();
1589 flowDate = paymentCalendar.advance(flowDate, paymentLag, Days, paymentConvention);
1590 Real initNom = (excludeIndexing ? unpackIndexedCoupon(coupon2) : coupon2)->nominal();
1591 Real newNom = (excludeIndexing ? unpackIndexedCoupon(coupon) : coupon)->nominal();
1592 Real flow = initNom - newNom;
1593 if (flow != 0)
1594 leg.push_back(boost::shared_ptr<CashFlow>(new SimpleCashFlow(flow, flowDate)));
1595 }
1596 }
1597
1598 // Final Nominal Return at Maturity
1599 if (finalNomFlow) {
1600 auto coupon = boost::dynamic_pointer_cast<QuantLib::Coupon>(refLeg.back());
1601 QL_REQUIRE(coupon, "makeNotionalLeg does not support non-coupon legs");
1602 double finalNomFlow = (excludeIndexing ? unpackIndexedCoupon(coupon) : coupon)->nominal();
1603 Date finalDate = coupon->accrualEndDate();
1604 finalDate = paymentCalendar.advance(finalDate, paymentLag, Days, paymentConvention);
1605 if (finalNomFlow != 0)
1606 leg.push_back(boost::shared_ptr<CashFlow>(new SimpleCashFlow(finalNomFlow, finalDate)));
1607 }
1608
1609 return leg;

110 << i << " (" << fixingDates[i]
111 << ") must be less or equal to reset date at " << i << " ("
112 << resetDates[i] << ")");
113 QL_REQUIRE(resetDates[i] <= calcDates.back(), "makeNonStandardIborLeg(): reset date at "
114 << i << " (" << resetDates[i]
115 << ") must be less or equal last calculation date ("
116 << calcDates.back());
117 }
118
119 for (Size i = 0; i < calcDates.size() - 1; ++i) {
120 QL_REQUIRE(calcDates[i] <= calcDates[i + 1], "makeNonStandardIborLeg(): calc date at "
121 << i << " (" << calcDates[i]
122 << ") must be less or equal calc date at " << (i + 1) << " ("
123 << calcDates[i + 1]);
124 }
125
126 for (Size i = 0; i < fixingDates.size() - 1; ++i) {
127 QL_REQUIRE(fixingDates[i] <= fixingDates[i + 1], "makeNonStandardIborLeg(): fixing date at "
128 << i << " (" << fixingDates[i]
129 << ") must be less or equal fixing date at " << (i + 1)
130 << " (" << fixingDates[i + 1] << ")");
131 }
132
133 for (Size i = 0; i < resetDates.size() - 1; ++i) {
134 QL_REQUIRE(resetDates[i] <= resetDates[i + 1], "makeNonStandardIborLeg(): reset date at "
135 << i << " (" << resetDates[i]
136 << ") must be less or equal reset date at " << (i + 1)
137 << " (" << resetDates[i + 1] << ")");
138 }
139
140 // build calculation periods including broken periods due to notional resets or fixing resets
141
142 std::set<Date> effCalcDates;
143
144 for (auto const& d : calcDates)
145 effCalcDates.insert(d);
146
147 for (auto const& d : resetDates)
148 effCalcDates.insert(d);
149
150 if (strictNotionalDates)
151 for (auto const& d : notionalDates) {
152 effCalcDates.insert(d);
153 }
154
155 // build coupons
156
157 Leg leg;
158
159 for (auto startDate = effCalcDates.begin(); startDate != std::next(effCalcDates.end(), -1); ++startDate) {
160
161 // determine calc end date from start date
162
163 Date endDate = *std::next(startDate, 1);
164
165 // determine pay date
166
167 auto nextCalcDate = std::lower_bound(calcDates.begin(), calcDates.end(), endDate);
168 QL_REQUIRE(nextCalcDate != calcDates.begin(),
169 "makeNonStandardIborLeg(): internal error, nextCalcDate == calcDates.begin(), contact dev.");
170 Date payDate = payDates[std::distance(calcDates.begin(), nextCalcDate) - 1];
171
172 // determine reset and thereby fixing date
173
174 auto nextReset = std::upper_bound(resetDates.begin(), resetDates.end(), *startDate);
175 QL_REQUIRE(nextReset != resetDates.begin(),
176 "makeNonStandardIborLeg(): calc start date "
177 << *startDate << " is before first reset date " << *resetDates.begin()
178 << ". Ensure that there is a reset date on or before the calc start date.");
179 Date fixingDate = fixingDates[std::distance(resetDates.begin(), nextReset) - 1];
180
181 // determine notional
182
183 auto notionalDate = std::upper_bound(notionalDates.begin(), notionalDates.end(), *startDate);
184 Real notional = notionals[std::distance(notionalDates.begin(), notionalDate)];
185
186 // determine spread
187
188 auto spreadDate = std::upper_bound(spreadDates.begin(), spreadDates.end(), *startDate);
189 Real spread = spreads[std::distance(spreadDates.begin(), spreadDate)];
190
191 // determine gearing
192
193 auto gearingDate = std::upper_bound(gearingDates.begin(), gearingDates.end(), *startDate);
194 Real gearing = gearings[std::distance(gearingDates.begin(), gearingDate)];
195
196 // build coupon
197
198 leg.push_back(boost::make_shared<IborCoupon>(payDate, notional, *startDate, endDate, fixingDate, index, gearing,
199 spread, Date(), Date(), dayCounter));
200 }
201
202 return leg;
203}

353 // To be able to construct CDS schedules with front or back stub periods, we overwrite the
354 // first (last) date of the schedule built in QL with a given first (last) date
355 // The schedule builder in QL itself is not capable of doing this, it just throws an exception
356 // if a first (last) date is given in combination with a CDS / CDS2015 date generation rule.
357 std::vector<Date> dates = Schedule(startDate, endDate, tenor, calendar, bdc, bdcEnd, rule, endOfMonth).dates();

401 schedules.push_back(makeSchedule(d));
402 for (auto& r : data.rules())
403 schedules.push_back(makeSchedule(r, openEndDateReplacement));
404 if (!baseSchedules.empty())
405 for (auto& dv : data.derived()) {
406 auto baseSchedule = baseSchedules.find(dv.baseSchedule());
407 QL_REQUIRE(baseSchedule != baseSchedules.end(), "makeSchedule(): could not find base schedule \"" << dv.baseSchedule() << "\"");
408 schedules.push_back(makeSchedule(dv, baseSchedule->second));
409 }
410 QL_REQUIRE(!schedules.empty(), "No dates or rules to build Schedule from");
411 if (schedules.size() == 1)
412 // if we have just one, use that (most common case)
413 return schedules.front();
414 else {
415 // if we have multiple, combine them
416
417 // 1) sort by start date
418 std::sort(schedules.begin(), schedules.end(),
419 [](const Schedule& lhs, const Schedule& rhs) -> bool { return lhs.startDate() < rhs.startDate(); });
420
421 // 2) check if meta data is present, and if yes if it is consistent across schedules;
422 // the only exception is the term date convention, this is taken from the last schedule always
423 BusinessDayConvention convention = Null<BusinessDayConvention>(),
424 termConvention = Unadjusted; // initialization prevents gcc warning
425 Calendar calendar;
426 Period tenor;
427 DateGeneration::Rule rule = DateGeneration::Zero; // initialization prevents gcc warning
428 bool endOfMonth = false; // initialization prevents gcc warning
429 bool hasCalendar = false, hasConvention = false, hasTermConvention = false, hasTenor = false, hasRule = false,
430 hasEndOfMonth = false, hasConsistentCalendar = true, hasConsistentConvention = true,
431 hasConsistentTenor = true, hasConsistentRule = true, hasConsistentEndOfMonth = true;
432 for (auto& d : data.dates()) {
433 updateData<Calendar>(d.calendar(), calendar, hasCalendar, hasConsistentCalendar, parseCalendarTemp);
434 updateData<BusinessDayConvention>(d.convention(), convention, hasConvention, hasConsistentConvention,
435 parseBusinessDayConvention);
436 updateData<Period>(d.tenor(), tenor, hasTenor, hasConsistentTenor, parsePeriod);
437 }
438 for (auto& d : data.rules()) {
439 updateData<Calendar>(d.calendar(), calendar, hasCalendar, hasConsistentCalendar, parseCalendarTemp);
440 updateData<BusinessDayConvention>(d.convention(), convention, hasConvention, hasConsistentConvention,
441 parseBusinessDayConvention);
442 updateData<Period>(d.tenor(), tenor, hasTenor, hasConsistentTenor, parsePeriod);
443 updateData<bool>(d.endOfMonth(), endOfMonth, hasEndOfMonth, hasConsistentEndOfMonth, parseBool);
444 updateData<DateGeneration::Rule>(d.rule(), rule, hasRule, hasConsistentRule, parseDateGenerationRule);
445 if (d.termConvention() != "") {
446 hasTermConvention = true;
447 termConvention = parseBusinessDayConvention(d.termConvention());
448 }
449 }
450
451 // 3) combine dates and fill isRegular flag
452 const Schedule& s0 = schedules.front();
453 vector<Date> dates = s0.dates();
454 std::vector<bool> isRegular(s0.dates().size() - 1, false);
455 if (s0.hasIsRegular())
456 isRegular = s0.isRegular();
457 // will be removed, if next schedule's front date is matching the last date of current schedule
458 isRegular.push_back(false);
459 for (Size i = 1; i < schedules.size(); ++i) {
460 const Schedule& s = schedules[i];
461 QL_REQUIRE(dates.back() <= s.dates().front(), "Dates mismatch");
462 // if the end points match up, skip one to avoid duplicates, otherwise take both
463 Size offset = dates.back() == s.dates().front() ? 1 : 0;
464 isRegular.erase(isRegular.end() - offset,
465 isRegular.end()); // correct for superfluous flags from previous schedule
466 // add isRegular information, if available, otherwise assume irregular periods
467 if (s.hasIsRegular()) {
468 isRegular.insert(isRegular.end(), s.isRegular().begin(), s.isRegular().end());
469 } else {
470 for (Size ii = 0; ii < s.dates().size() - 1; ++ii)
471 isRegular.push_back(false);
472 }
473 if (i < schedules.size() - 1) {
474 // will be removed if next schedule's front date is matching last date of current schedule
475 isRegular.push_back(false);
476 }
477 // add the dates
478 dates.insert(dates.end(), s.dates().begin() + offset, s.dates().end());
479 }
480
481 // 4) Build schedule
482 return Schedule(dates, hasCalendar && hasConsistentCalendar ? calendar : NullCalendar(),
483 hasConvention && hasConsistentConvention ? convention : Unadjusted,
484 hasTermConvention ? boost::optional<BusinessDayConvention>(termConvention) : boost::none,
485 hasTenor && hasConsistentTenor ? boost::optional<Period>(tenor) : boost::none,
486 hasRule && hasConsistentRule ? boost::optional<DateGeneration::Rule>(rule) : boost::none,
487 hasEndOfMonth && hasConsistentEndOfMonth ? boost::optional<bool>(endOfMonth) : boost::none,
488 isRegular);
489 }
490}

std::vector< Date > coarsenDateGrid ( const std::vector< Date > &  date,
const std::string &  rule,

)

coarsens given date grid starting at eval date using the given rule, which is of the form 3M(1W),1Y(1M),5Y(3M),10Y(1Y),50Y(5Y) the rough idea is out to 3M at least a 1W spacing is used, output 1Y a 1M spacing etc. for the exact algorithm that generates the coarsened grid, see the code

63 grid.push_back(std::make_pair(parsePeriod(tmp[0]), parsePeriod(tmp[1])));

◆ parseScriptedCommodityIndex()

boost::shared_ptr< QuantExt::CommodityIndex > parseScriptedCommodityIndex ( const std::string &  indexName,
const QuantLib::Date &  obsDate = Date() 
)

This method tries to parse an commodity index name used in the scripting context

0) COMM-name 1) COMM-name-YYYY-MM-DD

2) COMM-name-YYYY-MM

3) CMMM-name#N#D#Cal 4) COMM-name#N#D

5) COMM-name#N

6) COMM-name!N

Here 0) - 2) are corresponding to the usual ORE conventions while 3) - 6) are specific to the scripting module: Expressions of the form 3) - 5) are resolved to one of the forms 1) and 2) using a given commodity future expiry calculator as follows:

3) COMM-name#N#D#Cal is resolved to the (N+1)th future with expiry greater than the given obsDate advanced by D business days w.r.t. Calendar Cal, N >= 0 4) as 3), Cal is taken as the commodity index's fixing calendar 5) as 4), D is set to 0 if not given 6) COMM-name!N is resolved to the future with month / year equal to the obsDate and monthOffst = N, N >=0

Notice that the forms 1) and 2) can be parsed without an obsDate and a commodity future convention given. If no convention is given, the fixing calendar in the index is set to the NullCalendar. In case a commodity future convention is given for the name, the fixing calendar is set to the calendar from the convention.

TODO if the form is COMM-name-YYYY-MM, the day of month of the expiry date will be set to 01, consistently with the ORE index parser, even if a convention is present, that would allow us to determine the correct expiry date. Should we use that latter date in the returned index?

Forms 3) to 6) on the other hand require a commodity future convention in any case, and an obsDate.

570
571 boost::shared_ptr<CommodityIndex> res;

574 QL_REQUIRE(tokens.size() <= 4,

576 << indexName << "'");
577 QL_REQUIRE(convention,

579 QL_REQUIRE(obsDate != Date(), "parseScriptedCommodityIndex(): obsDate required for '" << indexName << "'");

586 Date adjustedObsDate = deliveryRollDays != 0 ? rollCal.advance(obsDate, deliveryRollDays * Days) : obsDate;

588 res = res->clone(expiryCalculator.nextExpiry(true, adjustedObsDate, offset));
589 } else if (tokens2.size() >= 2) {

591 QL_REQUIRE(tokens.size() <= 2,
592 "parseScriptedCommodityIndex(): expected COMM-Name!N, got '" << indexName << "'");
593 QL_REQUIRE(convention,
594 "parseScriptedCommodityIndex(): commodity future convention required for '" << indexName << "'");
595 QL_REQUIRE(obsDate != Date(), "parseScriptedCommodityIndex(): obsDate required for '" << indexName << "'");
596 int offset = std::stoi(tokens[1]);
597 ConventionsBasedFutureExpiry expiryCalculator(*convention);
598 res = parseCommodityIndex(commName, false, Handle<PriceTermStructure>(), fixingCalendar, true);
599 res = res->clone(expiryCalculator.expiryDate(obsDate, offset));
600 } else {
601 // handle 0), 1) and 2)
602 res = parseCommodityIndex(indexName, true, QuantLib::Handle<QuantExt::PriceTermStructure>(), fixingCalendar,
603 false);
604 }
605
606 TLOG("parseScriptCommodityIndex(" << indexName << "," << QuantLib::io::iso_date(obsDate) << ") = " << res->name());
607 return res;
608}

◆ parseScriptedInflationIndex()

std::pair< boost::shared_ptr< QuantLib::ZeroInflationIndex >, std::string > parseScriptedInflationIndex ( const std::string &  indexName)

This method tries to parse an inflation index name used in the scripting context

1) EUHICPXT 2) EUHICPXT::F 3) EUHICPXT::L

Here 1) is the original form used in ORE. This represents a non-interpolated index. 2,3) is the extended form including a flag indicating the interpolation F (flat, =1) or L (linear)

The function returns a ql inflation index accounting for the interpolation (but without ts attached), and the ORE index name without the #F, #L suffix.

◆ parseCorrelationFactor()

CorrelationFactor parseCorrelationFactor ( const std::string &  name)

Parse a correlation factor name. For example, a name like IR:EUR is parsed to a CorrelationFactor with type, name and index set to IR, EUR and 0 respectively. Note that the name is of the form type:name and the index is always set to 0 initially. The actual index is set separately.

841 boost::shared_ptr<CommodityFutureConvention> convention;
842 if (p.first) {
843
844 convention = boost::dynamic_pointer_cast<CommodityFutureConvention>(p.second);
845
846 if (!convention->indexName().empty())
847 indexName = convention->indexName();
848
849 // If we have provided OffPeakPowerIndexData, we use that to construct the off peak power commodity index.
850 if (convention->offPeakPowerIndexData()) {
851
852 const auto& oppIdxData = *convention->offPeakPowerIndexData();
853
854 if (expiry == Date()) {
855 // If expiry is still not set use any date (off peak index is calendar daily)
856 expiry = Settings::instance().evaluationDate();
857 }
858 string suffix = "-" + to_string(expiry);
859
860 auto offPeakIndex = boost::dynamic_pointer_cast<CommodityFuturesIndex>(parseCommodityIndex(
861 oppIdxData.offPeakIndex() + suffix, false));
862 auto peakIndex = boost::dynamic_pointer_cast<CommodityFuturesIndex>(parseCommodityIndex(
863 oppIdxData.peakIndex() + suffix, false));
864
865 auto index = boost::make_shared<OffPeakPowerIndex>(indexName, expiry, offPeakIndex, peakIndex,
866 oppIdxData.offPeakHours(), oppIdxData.peakCalendar(), ts);
867 IndexNameTranslator::instance().add(index->name(), hasPrefix ? name : "COMM-" + name);
868 DLOG("parseCommodityIndex(" << name << ") -> " << index->name() << " with expiry " << index->expiryDate());
869 return index;
870 }
871 }
872
873 // Create and return the required future index
874 boost::shared_ptr<CommodityIndex> index;
875 if (expiry != Date() || (convention && enforceFutureIndex)) {
876
877 // If expiry is empty, just use any valid expiry.
878 if (expiry == Date()) {
879 ConventionsBasedFutureExpiry feCalc(*convention);
880 expiry = feCalc.nextExpiry();
881 }
882
883 bool keepDays = convention && convention->contractFrequency() == Daily;
884
885 Calendar cdr = cal;
886 if (convention && cdr == NullCalendar()) {
887 cdr = convention->calendar();
888 }
889
890 auto basisCurve = ts.empty() ? nullptr :
891 boost::dynamic_pointer_cast<CommodityBasisPriceTermStructure>(*ts);
892
893 if (basisCurve) {
894 index = boost::make_shared<CommodityBasisFutureIndex>(indexName, expiry, cdr, basisCurve);
895 } else {
896 index = boost::make_shared<CommodityFuturesIndex>(indexName, expiry, cdr, keepDays, ts);
897 }
898
899
900
901 } else {
902 index = boost::make_shared<CommoditySpotIndex>(commName, cal, ts);
903 }
904 IndexNameTranslator::instance().add(index->name(), index->name());
905 DLOG("parseCommodityIndex(" << name << ") -> " << index->name() << " with expiry " << index->expiryDate());
906 return index;
907}

◆ getInflationSwapStart() [2/2]

QuantLib::Date getInflationSwapStart ( const QuantLib::Date &  asof,

Definition at line 52 of file inflationstartdate.cpp.

52 {
53
54 using IPR = InflationSwapConvention::PublicationRoll;
55
56 // If no roll schedule, just return (as of, convention's obs lag).
57 if (conv.publicationRoll() == IPR::None) {
58 return asof;
59 }
60
61 // Get schedule and check not empty
62 const Schedule& ps = conv.publicationSchedule();
63 QL_REQUIRE(!ps.empty(), "InflationCurve: roll on publication is true for "
64 << conv.id() << " but the publication schedule is empty.");
65
66 // Check the schedule dates cover the as of date.
67 const vector<Date>& ds = ps.dates();
68 QL_REQUIRE(ds.front() < asof, "InflationCurve: first date in the publication schedule ("
69 << io::iso_date(ds.front()) << ") should be before the as of date ("
70 << io::iso_date(asof) << ").");
71 QL_REQUIRE(asof < ds.back(), "InflationCurve: last date in the publication schedule ("
72 << io::iso_date(ds.back()) << ") should be after the as of date ("
73 << io::iso_date(asof) << ").");
74
75 // Find d such that d_- < asof <= d. If necessary, move to the next publication schedule date. We
76 // know that there is another date because asof < ds.back() is checked above.
77 auto it = lower_bound(ds.begin(), ds.end(), asof);
78 Date d = *it;
79 if (asof == d && conv.publicationRoll() == IPR::OnPublicationDate) {
80 d = *next(it);
81 }
82
83 // Move d back availability lag and the 15th of that month is the helper's start date.
84 // Note: the 15th of the month is specific to AU CPI. We may need to generalise later.
85 d -= conv.index()->availabilityLag();
86
87 return Date(15, d.month(), d.year());
88}

◆ xccyCurveName()

std::string xccyCurveName ( const std::string &  ccyCode)

For a given currency code, ccyCode, return the internal name for the cross currency based yield curve.

For a given currency code, ccyCode, this function returns __XCCY__-ccyCode. This curve, if available, is currently used in special cases to allow for separate discount curves when discounting the cashflows on cross currency interest rate swaps.
